.\" Manpage for proxyreaper
.\" Contact rt@debian.sh to correct errors or typos.
.TH PROXYREAPER 1 "2026-07-02" "Proxy Reaper 2.2.0" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
proxyreaper \- test proxies for availability, speed, and anonymity
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B proxyreaper
[\fIOPTIONS\fR]... [\fIURL\fR]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B proxyreaper
is a tool that tests HTTP, HTTPS, SOCKS4, and SOCKS5 proxies for
availability, response time, and anonymity level. It categorizes working
proxies by speed, resolves GeoIP (and optionally reverse DNS), supports
parallel testing, powerful result filtering, multiple export formats, and
automatic proxy list downloads.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BR \fIURL\fR
The URL to test the proxies against. If omitted, the \fItest_url\fR from the
configuration is used (default: https://www.google.com).
.TP
.BR \-p ", " \-\-proxy=\fIPROXY\fR
Proxy, comma-separated list, a \fB.txt\fR file (one proxy per line), or a glob
pattern such as \fBlists/*.txt\fR. Duplicate proxies are removed automatically.
Either this or \fB\-A\fR is required.
.TP
.BR \-t ", " \-\-timeout=\fISECONDS\fR
Connection/read timeout in seconds (default: 5).
.TP
.BR \-o ", " \-\-output=\fIFORMAT\fR
Save results in the given format. Available formats: \fBjson\fR, \fBcsv\fR,
\fBsqlite\fR (default: \fBcsv\fR). A plain-text file of the working proxies is
always written in addition.
.TP
.BR \-c ", " \-\-concurrent=\fICOUNT\fR
Number of concurrent checks (default: 10).
.TP
.BR \-d ", " \-\-debug
Enable detailed debug output (headers, connection details, per-proxy errors).
.TP
.BR \-l ", " \-\-reverse-lookup
Resolve each proxy IP to a hostname via reverse DNS (slower; hostname is shown
and stored).
.TP
.BR \-A ", " \-\-automatic-mode
Download proxy lists from the URLs configured in the \fB[proxysources]\fR
section.
.TP
.BR \-C ", " \-\-config
Create a default configuration file at ~/.proxyreaper.conf and exit.
.TP
.BR \-v ", " \-\-version
Display version information and exit.
.SH FILTER OPTIONS
Filters restrict what is written to the output files; they do not change what
is tested. Each option accepts multiple values (OR within an option), and
different filters combine (AND across options). Failed proxies are always
excluded from filtered output.
.TP
.BR \-\-filter-status " " \fISTATUS\fR...
Keep only these speed categories: \fBultrafast\fR, \fBfast\fR, \fBmedium\fR,
\fBslow\fR.
.TP
.BR \-\-filter-anonymity " " \fILEVEL\fR...
Keep only these anonymity levels: \fBhighanonymous\fR, \fBanonymous\fR,
\fBheaderleak\fR, \fBtransparent\fR.
.TP
.BR \-\-filter-protocol " " \fIPROTO\fR...
Keep only these protocols: \fBhttp\fR, \fBhttps\fR, \fBsocks4\fR, \fBsocks5\fR.
.TP
.BR \-\-filter-country " " \fICODE\fR...
Keep only proxies in these countries (via GeoIP), e.g. \fBde us uk\fR.
.TP
.BR \-\-filter-tld " " \fITLD\fR...
Keep only proxies whose GeoIP country maps to these TLDs, e.g. \fBde us uk\fR.
.PP
When any filter is active, output filenames are prefixed with
\fBfiltered_proxies_\fR instead of \fBproxy_results_\fR.
.SH CONFIGURATION
Proxy Reaper uses configuration files in the following order of precedence:
.TP
1. Command-line arguments
.TP
2. ~/.proxyreaper.conf (user-specific configuration)
.TP
3. /etc/proxyreaper.conf (system-wide configuration)
.TP
4. Default values
.PP
To create a default configuration file:
.PP
.nf
.RS
proxyreaper -C
.RE
.fi
.PP
The configuration file uses the INI format with the following sections:
.PP
.nf
.RS
[general]
timeout = 5
concurrent = 10
test_url = https://www.google.com

[output]
format = json
fast_only = false
save_directory = results

[proxysources]
urls = https://example.com/list1.txt, https://example.com/list2.txt

[advanced]
debug = false
anonymity_check_url = https://httpbin.org/get
.RE
.fi
.PP
Note: when \fB\-o\fR is not given, the effective output format is \fBcsv\fR.
The \fBanonymity_check_url\fR must echo the request IP and headers (like
https://httpbin.org/get).
.SH PROXY FORMATS
Proxy Reaper supports several proxy formats:
.TP
\fIhost:port\fR (e.g., 127.0.0.1:8080) - Defaults to the HTTP protocol
.TP
\fIprotocol://host:port\fR (e.g., socks5://127.0.0.1:1080)
.TP
\fIprotocol://username:password@host:port\fR (e.g., http://user:pass@127.0.0.1:8080)
.PP
Supported protocols:
.TP
\fBHTTP\fR
.TP
\fBHTTPS\fR
.TP
\fBSOCKS4\fR
.TP
\fBSOCKS5\fR
.SH SPEED CATEGORIES
Working proxies are categorized by measured response time:
.TP
\fBultrafast\fR
Less than 100 ms
.TP
\fBfast\fR
100 to 500 ms
.TP
\fBmedium\fR
500 to 1000 ms
.TP
\fBslow\fR
More than 1000 ms
.SH ANONYMITY LEVELS
Proxy Reaper categorizes proxies into different anonymity levels:
.TP
\fBHigh Anonymous\fR
Your IP address and proxy status are completely hidden
.TP
\fBAnonymous\fR
Your IP address is hidden, but the server knows you're using a proxy
.TP
\fBAnonymous (Header leak)\fR
Your IP is hidden, but proxy headers are visible
.TP
\fBTransparent\fR
Your original IP address is visible to the server
.SH OUTPUT FORMATS
Each result record contains: proxy, hostname, status, speed_category,
response_time, country, city, anonymity, protocol, check_time. Results are
written to the configured \fIsave_directory\fR (default: ./results/).
.TP
\fBJSON\fR
Detailed proxy information in JSON format
.TP
\fBCSV\fR
Tabular format suitable for spreadsheet applications (default format)
.TP
\fBSQLite\fR
SQLite database with a proxies table
.TP
\fBTXT\fR
Always written alongside the chosen format: the working proxies, one per line
.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
Test a single proxy:
.PP
.nf
.RS
proxyreaper https://www.google.com -p 1.2.3.4:8080
.RE
.fi
.TP
Test multiple proxies from a file and save as JSON:
.PP
.nf
.RS
proxyreaper https://www.google.com -p proxies.txt -o json
.RE
.fi
.TP
Test all lists matching a glob pattern with 20 workers:
.PP
.nf
.RS
proxyreaper https://www.google.com -p "lists/*.txt" -c 20
.RE
.fi
.TP
Reverse-DNS plus only high-anonymous SOCKS5 proxies, saved to SQLite:
.PP
.nf
.RS
proxyreaper -p proxies.txt -l -o sqlite --filter-protocol socks5 --filter-anonymity highanonymous
.RE
.fi
.TP
Download fresh lists and keep only fast German proxies:
.PP
.nf
.RS
proxyreaper -A --filter-status ultrafast fast --filter-country de
.RE
.fi
.SH FILES
.TP
.I ~/.proxyreaper.conf
User-specific configuration file
.TP
.I /etc/proxyreaper.conf
System-wide configuration file
.TP
.I ./results/
Default directory for saving results
